2.5 THE FFOWCS WILLIAMS & HAWKINGS’S ANALOGY
A generalization of Lighthill’s theory to include aerodynamic surfaces in motion, proposed by Ffowcs Williams & Hawkings ([6], 1969) has provided the basis for a significant amount of analysis of the noise produced by rotating blades, including helicopter rotors, propeller blades, and fans,
The Ffowcs Williams & Hawkings (FW-H) theory includes surface source terms in addition to the quadrupole-like source introduced by Lighthill. The surface sources are generally referred to as thickness (or monopole) sources and loading (or dipole) sources.
They are also often termed linear in that no explicitly nonlinear terms appear in them and the propagation from the surfaces has no nonlinear component. It should be noted, however, that the loading sources, which consist of surface pressures, may be computed using nonlinear aerodynamic methods.
